<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 ESCAPEES CAUGHT; 4 FROM BREAKOUT STILL FREE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANKI V. RANSOM, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two more inmates who participated in a mass escape from County Jail in Chula 
Vista were recaptured Tuesday in North Park by San Diego police. 
</P>
<P>
The arrests bring to nine the number of escapees from the March 7 breakout who 
have been recaptured. Four others remain at large. 
</P>
<P>
Police identified one of the men apprehended Tuesday as Larry Rodriguez 
Dominguez, 18. A suspected gang member, he was considered one of the most 
dangerous of the escapees. He was in jail on suspicion of murder, attempted 
murder, robbery and weapons violations. 
</P>
<P>
The other escapee caught Tuesday was Jesus Humberto Lopez, 21, who was in 
custody on charges of assault with a deadly weapon and sexual assault. 
</P>
<P>
Dominguez and Lopez are close friends, according to Police Department spokesman 
Bill Robinson, and the two men were arrested at the home of relatives of 
Dominguez in the 440 block of Park Boulevard, where they were living. 
</P>
<P>
About 11:30 a.m. Tuesday, detectives saw Lopez get in a car with another man, 
who took him to a McDonald's restaurant on El Cajon Boulevard near Interstate 
805. As they placed orders at the drive-through window, police used their 
vehicles to block them off. The driver, Frank Amador, was arrested on suspicion 
of harboring a fugitive. 
</P>
<P>
Detectives later returned to the house. Working with a task force of officers 
from homicide, special investigations, patrol units, plus a police helicopter 
unit, officers forced their way into the house about 1 p.m. and arrested 
Dominguez without incident. 
</P>
<P>
Sgt. Gordon Redding said several people were in the house, but the owners were 
not home. He said charges of harboring a fugitive are pending against the 
owners. 
</P>
<P>
"Before the escape took place, (Dominguez) made statements to people that he 
would kill any police officer that tried to arrest him," Redding said. 
"Sheriff's deputies at the Chula Vista facility warned us after the escape." 
</P>
<P>
Still at large are Francisco Yacumba, 19, who was in custody on drug charges; 
Audias Gomez, 36, held on murder charges; Benjamin Tapia, 21, accused of being 
a burglar, and Sergio Martinez, 22, an alleged murderer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA032190-0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 192521 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 21, 1990, Wednesday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
