<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. Weighs New Type of S&amp;L Support: Savings and loan regulators are 
considering a controversial program that would pump taxpayer dollars into 
ailing thrift institutions before they fail. The Federal Deposit Insurance 
Corp. chose eight states whose institutions would be eligible for open thrift 
assistance but postponed until next week approval of the program itself. The 
states, selected because they are economically depressed, are: Alaska, Arizona, 
Arkansas, Colorado, Louisiana, New Mexico, Oklahoma and Texas. 
</P>
