<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
TOUGH SMOG AMENDMENT KILLED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Despite warnings it was weakening existing law, the Senate refused today to 
require the Environmental Protection Agency to impose smog cleanup plans on 
cities that do not adopt tough enough anti-pollution measures. 
</P>
<P>
In another important victory for Senate leaders determined to protect their 
compromise clean air bill with the Bush Administration, senators voted 53-46 
against a plan by Sen. John Kerry (D-Mass.) to preserve the mandatory EPA 
enforcement provisions in the current Clean Air Act. 
</P>
<P>
Kerry's amendment also would have wiped out controversial sections of the 
compromise bill that would allow states to obtain emission reduction waivers 
from the EPA if necessary pollution control measures cost more than $5,000 per 
ton of pollutants eliminated. 
</P>
<P>
Environmental groups and more than a dozen governors lobbied senators to 
support Kerry's amendment, saying the compromise bill was too weak to ensure 
speedy cleanup of urban smog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
