<P>
BOOK HAS ENVIRONMENTAL BEAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There's an environmental tie-in with the new book on drums by Mickey Hart, one 
of the Grateful Dead's two drummers. 
</P>
<P>
"Drumming at the Edge of Magic: A Journey into the Spirit of Percussion," which 
will be published in September by Harper &amp; Row, is about the history and 
significance of drumming and Hart's travels around the world in pursuit of 
ancient and endangered drumming traditions. 
</P>
<P>
"It's a natural progression from learning about endangered music to caring 
about our endangered planet," says Hart. Therefore, because of Hart's concern 
for the environment, particularly rain forests, his publisher will plant two 
trees in a South American rain forest for every one tree required to produce 
his book. 
</P>
<P>
"Although obviously the paper used for book production doesn't come from rain 
forest trees, we see this action as a powerful symbol of our joint 
responsibility for replenishing natural resources," said Clayton Carlson, 
publisher of Harper &amp; Row in San Francisco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
