<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: THE HUMBLE ASPIRIN MAY BE THE WORLD'S WONDER DRUG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON, TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There is a wonder drug in your medicine cabinet and the chances are you don't 
even appreciate it. 
</P>
<P>
The greatest medication of all time was introduced in 1899 and even after 90 
years, medical science is still discovering new uses for the humble aspirin 
tablet. 
</P>
<P>
Back around the turn of the century, aspirin earned a reputation for relieving 
pain, lowering fever and reducing inflammation. Eighty years later researchers 
are discovering that aspirin may prevent heart attacks, migraine headaches, 
diabetic complications and maybe even Alzheimer's disease. 
</P>
<P>
In the Physicians' Health Study, 22,000 doctors were recruited. Half took one 
aspirin tablet every other day, while the other half received a placebo. The 
study was halted prematurely because the results were so impressive. 
</P>
<P>
The physicians receiving aspirin had only half as many heart attacks as the 
others, and the researchers felt it would be unethical to deprive their MD 
guinea pigs of this powerful prophylactic. 
</P>
<P>
Further analysis of the data reveals that the doctors on aspirin also suffered 
20% fewer migraine headaches. Although one aspirin every other day wouldn't 
halt a migraine in progress, it seemed to discourage these vicious headaches 
from getting started. 
</P>
<P>
Researchers suspect that aspirin works this magic by keeping blood platelets 
from sticking together. These cells are often responsible for blood clots that 
can trigger a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Richard Peto reported equally encouraging results from a study of British 
doctors. Aspirin-users had almost 30% fewer migraines. He suggests, "A migraine 
patient should consider taking a baby aspirin a day." 
</P>
<P>
Such a dose (80 mg -- one-fourth of a regular aspirin tablet) may end up being 
the optimal dose against heart attacks as well. Although most people find it 
hard to believe that such a tiny amount of ordinary aspirin could do anything, 
these very low doses have profound effects on the blood. 
</P>
<P>
A study of diabetics demonstrated that aspirin could slow deterioration of the 
tiny blood vessels feeding the retina of the eye. As a consequence, aspirin may 
help hold off damage to eyesight that is one of the serious consequences of 
diabetes. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the most extraordinary new use for aspirin may come from theories about 
Alzheimer's disease. Researchers are speculating that inflammation in the 
nervous system may be part of the process behind this destructive disease. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Patrick McGeer, professor of psychiatry at the University of British 
Columbia in Vancouver, Canada, observes that aspirin may prevent inflammation 
that leads to cell death in the brain. "I've never seen a rheumatoid arthritis 
patient with signs of Alzheimer's on autopsy," he notes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
